article.headline: Warriors win 10 of last 12 games
article.linkText: Fading Rockets drop fifth consecutive game
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- With their season-long success suddenly having deserted them, the Houston Rockets are fading fast. Troy Murphy scored 20 points, and the Golden State Warriors sent the reeling Rockets to their fifth straight loss -- 97-90 Tuesday night. "Our coach is very intense and nobody really wants to do wrong and that's where you get a lot of mistakes," Rockets guard Steve Francis said. "Sometimes for guys who don't play 40 minutes they're playing a little tentative. For us, as starters, it's important that we at least come out and try to set the tone." Jason Richardson added 19 points as the Warriors won for the 10th time in 12 games. Clifford Robinson had 10 points and a career-high 10 assists. Speedy Claxton added 16 points and Mike Dunleavy 12. Jim Jackson scored 19 points and Francis 18 for the Rockets, who are clinging to seventh place in the Western Conference playoff race. Houston, looking for its first playoff berth in five years, leads eighth-place Utah by just 1{ games. "We're not playing to win," said Houston's Cuttino Mobley, who added 11 points. "We're playing not to lose to save our spot. I don't know what it is: enthusiasm, urgency, a will to win or not to win." Nine years removed from their last NBA championship, the Rockets couldn't muster the effort to beat a team that has missed the playoffs the past 10 years. "When we start playing better, we'll get better results," said Houston coach Jeff Van Gundy. "Nothing is good enough right now." The Warriors, playing in front of their sixth sellout crowd buoyed by a large Asian contingent, played like a team with playoff hopes despite having been eliminated from postseason contention for over a week. "Making the playoffs were a focal point for us at the beginning at the season," said Warriors center Adonal Foyle. "We're going to fall short of that and that's frustrating. At the same time you have to respect the game and go hard." Houston was 13 games over .500 after beating Memphis, 88-80, on March 13, but the Rockets have lost nine of their past 12. Yao Ming, who declined to speak with the media for the first time this season, scored 15 points but didn't take advantage as Warriors' starting center Erick Dampier missed his third straight game. The 7-foot-6 center was 6-of-14 from the field with eight rebounds before fouling out with 1:03 left. Robinson even blocked Yao's dunk attempt with 3:18 remaining. "I think I got Manute (Bol) once but Yao is a much better athlete," said Robinson. A 12-2 run early in the second quarter gave the Warriors a double-digit lead. Claxton, playing for the first time in 21 games, sparked the rally with four points and a pair of free throws. The Warriors have been without a true point guard because of injuries to Claxton and Nick Van Exel. Jackson scored 12 of his points in the third quarter for Houston, but it didn't make much of a dent as Golden State took an 81-68 lead into the fourth quarter. The Rockets shot 50 percent from the floor in the first half while the Warriors shot 62 percent. Murphy was 6-of-8 from the field, scoring 14 of his points early.

Game notes
The Rockets waived F Charles Oakley, who made the trip to Oakland, before the game. ... American Idol contestant William Hung, dismissed early in the process, performed at halftime to a rousing ovation. ... Warriors G Avery Johnson missed his second straight game with a strained right hamstring. ... With 19,596 fans, the Warriors outdrew the A's, who were playing next door at the same time. The A's drew 13,217. ... The Rockets beat the Warriors 15 straight in the Bay Area before Golden State won on March 19.
